<p><strong>Why was it wrong? Why does your fix work?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Bug B</strong> — Every variable should fall back to a default when the player types nothing. Right now only <code>hero</code> is protected; <code>weapon</code> is left unsafe.</p>
<pre><code class="language-python">hero = game.ask(&quot;Hero?&quot;)
if hero == &quot;&quot;:
    hero = &quot;brave traveller&quot;

weapon = game.ask(&quot;Weapon?&quot;)
game.say(f&quot;{hero} holds a {weapon}.&quot;)
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Hint:</strong> <code>weapon</code> needs its own <code>if ... == "":</code> check.</p>
<p><strong>Write the fixed code:</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Why was it wrong? Why does your fix work?</strong></p>
<p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p><p class="ruled">&nbsp;</p>

<p><strong>Bug C</strong> — The empty-check should match a truly <strong>empty</strong> answer. Right now it checks for a single space, so an empty answer is not caught.</p>
<pre><code class="language-python">name = game.ask(&quot;Name?&quot;)
if name == &quot; &quot;:
    name = &quot;brave traveller&quot;
game.say(f&quot;Welcome, {name}.&quot;)
</code></pre>
<p><strong>Hint:</strong> <code>""</code> means nothing typed; <code>" "</code> means one space. Which one do you want here?</p>
